<!-- .SH "NAME" -->
<A name=>

     <H3>NAME</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
ccs-queryd - real-time access request management utility for TOMOYO Linux
<!-- .SH "SYNOPSIS" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=1>

     <H3>SYNOPSIS</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .B ccs-queryd -->
<B>ccs-queryd</B> <!-- .sp -->
<P>
<!-- .B ccs-queryd <remote_ip:remote_port> -->
<B>ccs-queryd &lt;remote_ip:remote_port&gt;</B> <!-- .SH "DESCRIPTION" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>DESCRIPTION</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
This program detects policy violations that occur in domains set to enforcing mode. The violation is displayed and a number of options are given to either grant or reject this request. Programs are frozen until a response is provided by the administrator.
<!-- .PP -->
<P>
This is useful when upgrading packages on the system so that errors can be avoided due to changes in permissions.
<!-- .PP -->
<P>
Never grant access requests unconditionally. Policy violations must be carefully analyzed to determine whether they are coming from a compromised process or malicious attacker.
<!-- .SH "OPTIONS" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>OPTIONS</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>&lt;remote_ip:remote_port&gt;</B>
<!-- .RS 4 -->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Instead of managing local policy violations, manage policy violations via an agent waiting at port <I>&lt;remote_port&gt;</I> on IP address <I>&lt;remote_ip&gt;</I>.
<!-- .RE -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .SH "EXAMPLES" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>EXAMPLES</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .B Handle local policy violations: -->
<B>Handle local policy violations:</B> <!-- .nf -->
<PRE>
ccs-queryd
<!-- .fi -->
</PRE>
<!-- .PP -->
<P>
<!-- .B Handle remote policy violations via an agent waiting at port 10000 on 192.168.1.1: -->
<B>Handle remote policy violations via an agent waiting at port 10000 on 192.168.1.1:</B> <!-- .nf -->
<PRE>
ccs-queryd 192.168.1.1:10000
<!-- .fi -->
</PRE>
<!-- .SH "NOTES" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>NOTES</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
Before this program can be invoked, it must be registered in <I>/proc/ccs/manager</I>. After initializing policy, this is usually as simple as rebooting the system.
